Jojo Rabbit

2019

Directed by Taika Waititi

Synopsis

It’s definitely not a good time to be a Nazi.

A World War II satire that follows a lonely German boy whose world view is turned upside down when he discovers his single mother is hiding a young Jewish girl in their attic. Aided only by his idiotic imaginary friend, Adolf Hitler, Jojo must confront his blind nationalism.

Review by Karsten ★★★★½ Liked 37

Unexpectedly phenomenal. An absurd amount of passion and heart put into a film that shouldn’t work at all but miraculously does. Something no filmmaker besdies Watiti could pull off in this way. I’d go from embarrassingly scream laughing at Hitler jumping out of a window to being on the verge of tears. A breath of fresh air for this subject matter. If there was a film that truly felt like it needed to happen in 2019, it was Jojo Rabbit.

Review by Jack_Roney ★★★★½ Liked

This review may contain spoilers. I can handle the truth.

This movie is the perfect example of how everything is not black and white. It perfectly resembles how I would imagine a ten year-old Nazi kid experiencing the destruction of his town, finding a Jew in his house and having an imaginary Hitler as a friend. It all makes so much sense. Kids in Nazi Germany truly idolized Hitler and wanted to serve him in any way possible, so one of said kids having him as an imaginary friend works really well. Captain K is also a huge highlight for me. He went from begging to serve Nazi Germany to saving Jojo and Elsa(Jew in the house) from death. It’s a shame that we didn’t get a lot of screen… more
